<|channel>thought
<channel|>To be honest, being a student in Hong Kong is already very hard. Every day I have to wake up at 6:30 AM, take the MTR, and study for many many hours. But for me, it is even more difficult because I have a big secret. I am not just a normal student from a secondary school. I am actually a wood elf.

In my real home, the forest is very quiet and the air smells like rain and old leaves. But here, the air smells like diesel from the buses and fried egg from the canteen. Sometimes, I feel very lonely because I cannot tell my friends.

My name is Leo. In school, I wear the white shirt and the blue trousers. I try to look very normal. But my ears... they are a bit pointy. So, I always wear my hair long and messy. My classmates think I am just a "cool boy" who doesn't care about hair style, but actually, I am just hiding my elf ears!

The hardest part is the PE class (Physical Education). My teacher, Mr. Wong, always tells us to run laps around the track. For normal students, it is very tiring. But for a wood elf, my legs are made for running through trees and jumping over roots. When I run, I feel like I am flying. I have to try very hard to look tired and breathe heavily, otherwise, my classmates will think, "Why is Leo so fast? He is like a deer!"

One day, during the mid-term exam, the classroom was very hot. The air conditioner was broken. I could feel my magic starting to stir because I was stressed. When I am stressed, small green leaves sometimes grow from my skin. I saw a tiny leaf growing near my wrist! I quickly pulled my sleeve down and felt my heart beating very fast. *Oh no, please don't let anyone see,* I thought.

Then, something happened. My best friend, Kevin, was crying quietly at his desk. He failed his math test again. He is a good boy, but math is very hard for him. I felt a strange feeling in my chest. It is the "forest heart" feeling. I wanted to help him, but I don't have magic to change his grades.

So, I did something small. I used a little bit of my wood elf power. I didn't do anything big, just a tiny bit of nature magic. I focused on the small potted plant on the teacher's desk. I whispered a tiny word in my language. Suddenly, the plant grew a little bit faster and its leaves became very bright and green. A very sweet, calming smell of sandalwood came from the plant.

Kevin stopped crying. He looked at the plant and took a deep breath. "Wow, this plant smells so good," he said. He looked a bit more relaxed.

I smiled secretly. I cannot tell him that I am an elf, and I cannot take him to the magical forest. But I can use my secret to make his school life a little bit better.

School is still very busy, and I still have many homeworks to do. But even in this big, noisy city, I can find a way to bring a little bit of the forest to my classroom. [end of text]


